5.1 Understanding and Interpreting Two-way ANOVA

We can treat an interaction ANOVA model just like how we do with moderated regression.

  • For non-sig model, it’s a common practice to drop the interaction and run a normal model to test the main effects of our predictors.
  • For sig model, we interpret the interaction effect, conduct pairwise comparison, and graph the results.

EFFECTS OF THE DAY

  • Main Effects The effect of one predictor, ignoring (controlling for) the other predictor. In this example, it is the mean difference in Variable1 between Alcohol Consumption groups, ignoring whether someone is male or female. In other words, we compare the mean of the three Alcohol Consumption groups, averaged across sexes.
  • Simple Effects The effect of one predictor, conditioned on the level of another predictor. In this example, it is the mean difference in Variable1 between Alcohol Consumption groups, for males and females, respectively.
  • Interaction Effects The effect of one predictor, dependent on the level of another predictor. It concerns with how Variable1 differs based on levels of Alcohol Consumption and whether someone is male or female.

5.1.1 Non-significant two-way ANOVA

As usual, we drop the interaction and run multiple regression/ANOVA model.

mns <- lm(Variable1 ~ AUDITCat + Sex, data = d)
summary(mns)

5.1.2 Significant two-way ANOVA

When our model is significant, we interpret interaction effect. A significant p-value in an ANOVA test shows that some of the group means differ, but we don’t know which pairings of groups differ. Multiple pairwise comparisons can be performed to see if the mean differences between certain pairs of groups are statistically significant.

5.1.2.1 Pairwise comparison

5.1.2.1.1 Pairwise comparison for the interaction effect.

First, we obtain the estimated marginal means using emmeans().

em <- emmeans(m, c("AUDITCat", "Sex"), adjust = "bonferroni")

We can then obtain our multiple pairwise comparisons by summarising the results.

summary(em , infer = TRUE)

5.1.2.2 Visualising resutls

As usual, visreg can be used to graph the results from the lm model. Here, we separate our results by males and females.

visreg(m,
       xvar = "AUDITCat", by = "Sex",
       overlay = FALSE, partial = FALSE, band = TRUE, rug = FALSE, gg = TRUE) +
  ylab("Variable1") + xlab("Alcohol Consumption")

Alternatively, we can use the emmip() function to graph our result. We now separate our results by levels of alcohol consumption

emmip(em, ~ Sex | AUDITCat, CIs = TRUE) +
  ylab("Variable1") + xlab("Alcohol Consumption")
